Part 2 -Ash Framework For Phoenix Developers — Domain & Resource

Kamaro Lambert
12 min read
·
Jan 31, 2025

Previously we looked at thinking in Ash framework.

Let’s start by understanding the data representing our help center application. As we saw it in the previous sections, we’ll need to describe our application using Resource and Domain. Each data table will correspond to a resource and all below tables will be grouped together under a domain we’ll call KnowledgeBase.

But, the magic is that we’ll model all below entity relationship diagrams and let Ash create migrations, relationships, columns, validations and the rest for us. So observe below ERD carefully and let’s meet in the next section to implement it.

Define the Domain. House For Resources

To get started we need to define a domain called KnowledgeBase

It’s knowledge base because it houses knowledge for our helpcenter application. So from your root directory, go to lib/helpcenter and create knowledge_base.ex file and add below codes.

defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase do
  use Ash.Domain # ← Indicates that this file is Ash resource

  # `resources` is a macro A.K.A DSL to indicate that this sections lists resources under this domain, at the moment we have 0 resource so we'll leave it empty
  resources do
  end
end

Our domain is ready, now we need to tell our application that a new domain has been added, to do so we go to config/config.exs and add Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase to ash_domains to indicate that we have a new domain in the applications.

# config/config.exs
config :helpcenter,
ecto_repos: [Helpcenter.Repo],
generators: [timestamp_type: :utc_datetime],
ash_domains: [Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase] # ← Add this

Now that we have the domain ready, we proceed to adding resources to the domain, but before that, we need to define resources corresponding to each table as per our ERD above.

Defining Resource — Modeling our Database

In other frameworks tables are represented by models. In the Ash framework tables are represented by Resources. So we need to create a resource for each table.

Create a knowledge_base directory under lib/helpcenter. It is recommended that the resources under domain be put under a directory with the same name as the domain. So, we’ll host our resources under lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base.

So let’s create each resource one by one.

Category resource

Start by creating a lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/category.ex and add below codes:

# lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/category.ex
defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category do
  use Ash.Resource,
    # Tell Ash that this resource belongs to KnowledgeBase domain
    domain: Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase,
    # Tell Ash that this resource data is stored in a postgresql
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer

  postgres do
    # Tell Ash that this resource data is stored in a table named "categories"
    table "categories"
    # Tell Ash that this resource access data storage via Helpcenter.Repo
    repo Helpcenter.Repo
    # Delete related articles when a category is destroyed to prevent
    # leave records behind
    references do
      reference :articles, on_delete: :delete
    end
  end

  # Tell Ash what columns the resource has and their types and validations
  attributes do
    uuid_primary_key :id
    attribute :name, :string, allow_nil?: false
    attribute :slug, :string
    attribute :description, :string, allow_nil?: true
    # Automatically adds, inserted_at and updated_at columns
    timestamps()
  end

  # Relationship Block. In this case this resource has many articles
  relationships do
    has_many :articles, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
      description "Relationship with the articles."
      # Tell Ash that the articles table has a column named "category_id" that references this resource
      destination_attribute :category_id 
    end
   end
End

That’s it! You are becoming an Ash framework expert.

Now that we know how to create an Ash resource. Go ahead and create resources for the remainder of the resources.

Article Resource

# lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/article.ex
defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer

  postgres do
    table "articles"
    repo Helpcenter.Repo
  end

  attributes do
    uuid_primary_key :id
    attribute :title, :string, allow_nil?: false
    attribute :slug, :string
    attribute :content, :string
    attribute :views_count, :integer, default: 0
    attribute :published, :boolean, default: false
    # Automatically adds, inserted_at and updated_at columns
    timestamps()
  end

  relationships do
    belongs_to :category, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category do
      source_attribute :category_id
      allow_nil? false
    end

    has_many :comments, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Comment do
      destination_attribute :article_id
    end

    # Many-to-many relationship with Tag
    many_to_many :tags, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Tag do
      through Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleTag
      source_attribute_on_join_resource :article_id
      destination_attribute_on_join_resource :tag_id
    end

    has_many :article_feedbacks, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleFeedback do
      destination_attribute :article_id
    end
  end
end

Comments Resource

# lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/comment.ex
defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Comment do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer

  postgres do
    table "comments"
    repo Helpcenter.Repo
  end

  attributes do
    uuid_primary_key :id
    attribute :content, :string, allow_nil?: false
    timestamps()
  end
  relationships do
    belongs_to :article, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
      source_attribute :article_id
      allow_nil? false
    end
  end
End

Tags Resource

defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Tag do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer

  postgres do
    table "tags"
    repo Helpcenter.Repo
  end

  attributes do
    uuid_primary_key :id
    attribute :name, :string, allow_nil?: false
    attribute :slug, :string
    timestamps()
  end

  relationships do
    many_to_many :articles, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
      through Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleTag
      source_attribute_on_join_resource :tag_id
      destination_attribute_on_join_resource :article_id
    end
  end
end

Article Tag Resource


# lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/article_tag.ex
defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleTag do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer

  postgres do
    table "article_tags"
    repo Helpcenter.Repo
  end

  actions do
    default_accept [:article_id, :tag_id]
    defaults [:create, :read, :update, :destroy]
  end

  attributes do
    uuid_primary_key :id
    timestamps()
  end

  relationships do
    belongs_to :article, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
      source_attribute :article_id
    end

    belongs_to :tag, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Tag do
      source_attribute :tag_id
    end
  end

  identities do
    identity :unique_article_tag, [:article_id, :tag_id]
  end
end

ArticleFeedback

# lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/article_feedback.ex
defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleFeedback do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer

  postgres do
    table "article_feedbacks"
    repo Helpcenter.Repo
  end

  attributes do
    uuid_primary_key :id

    attribute :helpful, :boolean, default: false
    attribute :feedback, :string, allow_nil?: true

    create_timestamp :created_at
  end

  relationships do
    belongs_to :article, Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article do
      source_attribute :article_id
      allow_nil? false
    end
  end
end

Finally, let’s go back to our domain and tell the domain what resources are under it so that we can start to use our resources. Edit your domain to look like the following.

# lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base.ex
defmodule Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase do
  # <-- Indicates that this file is Ash resource
  use Ash.Domain

  # `resources` is a macro A.K.A DSL to indicate that this sections lists resources under this domain
  resources do
    # `resource` is a marco indicating a resource under this domain
    resource Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
    resource Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Article
    resource Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Tag
    resource Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleTag
    resource Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Comment
    resource Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.ArticleFeedback
  end
end

Generate Your Database With a Simple Command

At this point your resources and domains are read to:

  1. Generate migrations
  2. Created tables in the database with constraints
  3. Add relationships to the tables in the database.

But, your database connection has to be configured if you haven’t done it yet. So head to your config/dev.exs since you are in the local development environment and configure your database connection accordingly. It should look like the following.

# Configure your database
config :helpcenter, Helpcenter.Repo,
  username: System.get_env("PGUSER", "your database username"),
  password: System.get_env("PGPASSWORD", "your database password"),
  database: System.get_env("PGDATABASE", "helpcenter_dev"),
  hostname: System.get_env("PGHOST", "localhost"),
  port: System.get_env("PGPORT", "5432"),
  stacktrace: true,
  show_sensitive_data_on_connection_error: true,
  pool_size: 10

Once configuration is done run the following command.

  1. mix ash.setupfrom your root directory to setup Ash framework and create database if it does not exists. Then
  2. mix ash_postgres.generate_migrations — name add_knowledge_base_tables

The above 2 commands will do 2 things:

  1. Set up the data layer for ash.
  2. 2 Generate migrations for the database

Finally you run your migration to create actual tables in the database by running the mix ash_postgres.migratecommand.

Actions: Defines What Can Be Done On a Resource

Now that your resources, domain, database and its tables are set up, you are able to start using the Ash framework.

Previously we have been doing the setup. But now, we need to indicate how we want our application to work. For the sake of simplicity we’ll use Category resources in this section. What you will do with a category resource, you can do with any other resource and eventually we’ll do it down the line.

To work with the category resource we need to define actions!

Actions are the tasks or if you like the work that can be performed on a resource. They come in 5 categories: create, read, update, destroy and generic actions.

Let’s go back to our resources and define actions for each resource.

We do that by adding a block called actions in the resource. So head to the Category resource and add it, then define what actions are allowed.

To make this simple, we are going to define default actions.

Open lib/helpcenter/knowledge_base/category.ex and add the following section above the attributes block.

actions do
  # Tell Ash what columns to accept while inserting or updating
  default_accept [:name, :slug, :description]
  # Tell Ash what actions are allowed on this resource
  defaults [:create, :read, :update, :destroy]
end

This section tells Ash that you can perform actions of reading, destroying, creating, and updating on the Categoryresource. Since create and update always requires inputs, we also need to indicate what attributes are writable on this resource, thus defining default_accept

Creating a Record With Ash.Create

From your root directory, run iex -S mix to start interactive Elixir shell.

We’ll be using this interface until we create a user interface to run in the browser. For now, this is sufficient. After running the above command you will see the following interface.

To create a category, we’ll need to define category data using Elixir Map, then use Ash to create it in the database. Let’s see how it works.

Get Kamaro Lambert’s stories in your inbox

Join Medium for free to get updates from this writer.

Define data to insert in the database

category_params = %{name: "Billing", slug: "billing", description: "Refund requests, billings and account issues"}

Then, in your open shell run the following command to insert the data in the database.

Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Changeset.for_create(:create, category_params)
|> Ash.create()

You should see the results below if all went well!

You just inserted your first category data in the database. Let’s break it down to understand what has just happened.

We wrote 3 lines after defining our data.

  1. Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category indicates what table or resources we are targeting
  2. Ash.Changeset.for_create(:create, category_params) tells ash that we want to perform an action of type create which will insert data provided in category_params in the database.

If you are new to the|> operator. The above two lines can also be written as: Ash.Changeset.for_create(Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category, :create, category_params).

We’ll talk more about the changesets later, for now, know that the first 2 lines is for preparing data to store in the data layer.

Finally, we passed the result of the first 2 lines into Ash.create() to persist the data in the database. As you can see on the screenshot that behind the scene Ash runs the insert query.

Congratulations! You have just inserted your first data into the Ash framework, next, we’ll see how to read data and how to update data.

Reading Record(s) with Ash.read

Ash provides different ways of reading and returning data. But, all of them can be defined into 2 categories. One returns many results such as a list of records, while another returns one record.

To read resource data without filtering you just pass your resource to Ash.read(ResourceName). Then Ash will retrieve all available data.

It’s same as running SELECT * FROM your_table.

Let’s take an example with the category resource.

From your iex console, run Ash.read(Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category) to return a list of categories.

Note that it returns a tuple of {:ok, results}. If you want the list without the tuple you can add ! like Ash.read!(Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category)

Use Ash.read_first(Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category)to get the first record in the table, or Ash.get(ResourceName, primary_key) to retrieve records by primary key. See example below.

But what if you want to filter your records based on attributes other than the primary key? That’s what we are seeing next.

Conditional with Ash.Query.filter

In real-life, we filter data based on different available attributes. For example, we can filter categories by their name, slug, description, timestamps or even combine all of them.

In SQL we use WHERE condition to do that. In Ash we use Ash.Query.filter to do that.

Ash.Query has many other functions such as sort equivalent to limit in SQL and many more. But for now, we’ll only focus on retrieving data conditionally using Ash.Query.filter.

Let’s see it in action.

Let’s say that we want to retrieve categories by name, slug or description. First we need to have more data in the database in order to have what to filter against. Go to your iex and paste the following data and press enter:

attrs = [
  %{
    name: "Account and Login",
    slug: "account-login",
    description: "Help with account creation, login issues, and profile management"
    },
  %{

    slug: "billing-payments",

   },

    description: "Guides and support for employee onboarding, time-off, and payroll"
    },

    },
    %{
    name: "Inventory Management",
    slug: "inventory-management",
    description: "Support for stock tracking, warehouse management, and orders"
    },
    %{
    name: "Production and Manufacturing",
    slug: "production-manufacturing",
    description: "Guides for managing production schedules, resources, and outputs"
    },

Then call: Ash.Seed.seed!(Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category, attrs) to seed data in the database. If all went well, you should see the results of the created data on your console. Now, you have data you can query and filter against.

NB: You must require Ash.Query before you can use Ash.Query.filter

To filter categories whose name is “General Support”, you will do it like the following.

# Require the Ash.Query in order to use its macros
require Ash.Query
# Now that we have all Ash.Query macros we can use it however we want
Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Query.filter(name == "General Support")
|> Ash.read()

The above should give you results that look like the following, showing you what query was run on the database and returning the results.

Notice how it returned a tuple of {:ok, []}? This is because Ash.read/1 returns a list of records. To return the first category matching the conditions you can replace Ash.read/1 with Ash.read_first/1.

Noted: You can chain queries however you want like in the following:

Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Query.filter(name == "General Support")
|> Ash.Query.filter(slug == "general-support")
|> Ash.read()

We’ll see more complex filtering along the way. Next, let’s see how to update a record in the database.

Update Record(s) with Ash.Update

In the previous section, we learnt how to use Ash.Query to read the data. By now, you might have learnt that we use Ash.Query to read data while we use Ash.Changeset to create new data or updating existing data in the database. Since the update changes existing data, we’ll use the Ash.Changeset.

We won’t want to update all records in the database, thus we need to:

  1. Specify what data to be updated in the database.
  2. What action to use while updating the data.
  3. What attributes and their new corresponding data.

Let’s say that we want to update the category name of “System Setup and Integration” to “Integration”. We can do it by the following codes:

require Ash.Query
# 1. Get category to update
category =
Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Query.filter(name == "System Setup and Integration")
|> Ash.read_first!()

# 2. Update category name in the database
category
|> Ash.Changeset.for_update(:update, %{name: "Integration"})
|> Ash.update()

The above can also be chained like the following.

# 1. Get category to update
Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Query.filter(name == "System Setup and Integration")
|> Ash.read_first!()
# Update category name in the database
|> Ash.Changeset.for_update(:update, %{name: "Integration"})
|> Ash.update()

In nutshell you will need to identify record(s) to update, then tell ash to build a changeset for updating, specify what action to use then, tell ash to update in the database.

Destroying Record(s) with Ash.Destroy

So far, you should be able to create, read, update and now we are going to learn how to delete or permanently destroy data.

To destroy data, you will need to specify what record you want to destroy, thus here are the steps:

  1. Fetch the record to destroy
  2. Pass the results to Ash.destroy

Let’s see it in action:

# First identify category to destroy
category_to_delete =
Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Query.filter(name == "Approvals and Workflows")
|> Ash.read_first!()

# Tell Ash to destroy it
Ash.destroy(category_to_delete)

And as you might have noticed, we can also chain the above codes into the following. Both do the same

Helpcenter.KnowledgeBase.Category
|> Ash.Query.filter(name == "Approvals and Workflows")
|> Ash.read_first!()
|> Ash.destroy()

What we’ve done with categories so far, can also be done with Tags.

To cement your learning, I recommend you try to do CRUD with tags by yourself. Next we are going to work with relationships.

Next, we’ll be looking into the Relationship.
